Where I live in Pennsylvania, vets have had watchfire/barnfire ceremonies in the fall.  The tradition as I understand it was used by the American Army in the Revolutionary War to set a bright light at night to guide lost soldiers back to their camps.  I have learned in my history studies that the tradition went as far back as the Romans (perhaps the Greeks).  Fire was a shining light at night, a giver of warmth and security.  Fire was always used to guide others to safety and away from danger.  I've seen vets use barnfires as a sort of symbolic rememberance to those who lost lives, the missing in action, and those who are still seeking a way home.  It's a link to the warrior spirit and power of the past, a deep rooted connection and manifestation of the intangible properties of the human spirit (sorry if I get philosophical).  <br><br>
Anyway, I think it is a nice thing to do and wished more people did it.
